qas.question: Prior to the naming of Miami, what was the area around Miami called?
When did the Great Freeze occur?
What railroad was owned by Henry Flagler?
Prior to the naming of Miami, what wasn't the area around Miami called?
When did the Great Thaw occur?
What railroad was disowned by Henry Flagler?

context: Miami is noted as "the only major city in the United States conceived by a woman, <a4_0>Julia Tuttle<a4_0/>", a local citrus grower and a wealthy <a0_0><b5_0>Cleveland<b5_0/><a0_0/> native. The Miami area was better known as "<a1_0><b6_0>Biscayne Bay Country<b6_0/><a1_0/>" in the early years of its growth. In the late 19th century, reports described the area as a promising wilderness. The area was also characterized as "one of the finest building sites in Florida." The Great Freeze of <a2_0><b7_0>1894–95<b7_0/><a2_0/> hastened Miami's growth, as the crops of the Miami area were the only ones in Florida that survived. <b9_0>Julia Tuttle<b9_0/> subsequently convinced Henry Flagler, a railroad tycoon, to expand his <a3_0><b8_0>Florida East Coast Railway<b8_0/><a3_0/> to the region, for which she became known as "the mother of Miami." Miami was officially incorporated as a city on July 28, 1896 with a population of just over 300. It was named for the nearby Miami River, derived from Mayaimi, the historic name of Lake Okeechobee.
